Message:Cadets,

As a reminder drill team now counts for honor points, 5 per cadet. If you attended the last practice, it will count.

If you would like to attend, we hold practice every Friday 1600-1700, and we meet in the cadet lounge at 1555.

Why do drill team?
1. Prepare for FT.
2. Increase drill proficiency, command voice.
3. You will do outstanding things. Think throwing rifles, armed exhibition.  We are aiming for the sky. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=61EX4AC-L1k

Message:After days of watching other people participate (and not thinking my day would come), I was nominated to the do the ALS ice bucket challenge by Dung Budam. To start, ALS is a neurodegenerative disease affecting the spinal cord and brain nerve cells and impacting 5600 people yearly in the US. For more information visit alsa.org. I nominate my handsome twin Jarrell McQueen , Andrew Alewine, and a special secret group of people who have made my first year awesome. They will know who they are. Y'all have 24 hours!:)

Message:Greetings, cadets! 

First off, I know everyone from our Squadron is not yet linked to our Facebook, so please share with them this information in this post. 

The purpose of this page is to share ideas, give information about social and volunteer events we can attend together as a squadron, how we're doing with honor squadron and warrior squadron, and motivate and encourage each other throughout the semester. I encourage you to not be afraid to share ideas you may have that you think we all will benefit from as a group. If anyone has any idea of what to do for our first initial group outing, go ahead and comment on this post. 

Just a reminder of who has what job in the squadron for this rotation:

Squadron Commander - C/3C Wilson
Deputy Squadron Commander - C/3C Hamlet
Academic Officer - C/3C Dinh
Physical Fitness Officer - C/3C McQueen
Health and Safety Officer - C/4C Fontalvo
Standardization Officer - C/4C Greth

C/3C McQueen will also be creating a phone tree for tomorrow morning. See you all dark and early!

Thank you everyone for being helpful this afternoon! That is a prime example of why we put so much emphasis on the wingman concept and the idea of accountability. I was able to very quickly determine that all of you were safe this afternoon, and I was able to make sure that I passed it up the chain. 

Get some sleep, and I'll see you all at PT!

If you are a 200 and have not had certain leadership roles please let me know. 100s, I will continue to rotate all of you into the flight positions as well, please let me know if you have preferences as we move into the last few rotations.

Name:Open Ranks Inspection
Story:N/A
Message:Alright! I have been a little bit of a slacker in the past few days, so here is a gigantic post.

It is time for the new flight positions.

CC - Hanha Hobson
CD - Chris Calderado
D&C - Michael Paul
STANDO - Sade' Wilson
ACADO - Connor Hamlet
SAFEO - Estelle McQueen
PFO - Alex Zorich

ORI

For Tuesday's ORI. You will all be in Service Dress. Please make sure you are looking up the regs and spending A LOT of time to make sure it is right. There is a lot to go wrong in the setup, and Cadre will find the mistakes.

I will be acting as the FLT/CC
Cadet Knight will be the deputy
The element leaders will be Cadets Strawser, Hobson, and Horman.
Cadet Calderado will be the guidon bearer.

YOU MUST STUDY THE PROCEDURES. This is not a Lead Lab to learn how to do an ORI. It is a Lead Lab to EXECUTE and ORI. Study with your flight mates, and ask plenty of questions before we start.
Watch this video: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mSuVRRPx0RM

Reveille and Retreat

These are happening on Tuesday. You will not need to learn or do much of anything that is not explicitly commanded, but READ THE OPS ORDERS. Reveille will be at 0715!

Guidon

We need to start working on this in earnest. We need to have a plan for our pole at least before Spring Break.

Lastly

WE ARE CLOSING THE GAP IN WARRIOR AND HONOR. Keep up the great work on that! Let's crush this inspection!

Message:I would like to officially welcome Cadet Connor Hamlet into Charlie Flight. 

I also have all of your Warrior Knowledge tests back from Cadet Horman, and I have to say, I am not impressed. Our flight average was a 68%. Cadet McQueen did the best of our flight, and out-scored every Field Training Prep Cadet. You 200s absolutely must step it up if you hope to be successful at FT. You have been learning this material for a long time, but I wouldn't have known that by looking at the grades. I am going to give you each back your test at PT tomorrow, and I want you to bring me the correct answers to all of the questions you missed on Monday morning. It is not a punishment, it is just more practice at your Warrior Knowledge.

Due to the number of Cadets from our flight that have left the program, I will be reassigning flight positions before PT tomorrow.

Please be safe out in the ice, and enjoy a little bit of a late start tomorrow! Stay posted for info about PT.

ID:1112091945_10200553577257881
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Got rejected from your dream college? I wonder how they would respond if you sent them this letter in return. Apparently someone did. 

Dear Admissions Committee:
Having reviewed the many rejection letters I have received in the last few weeks, it is with great regret that I must inform you I am unable to accept your rejection at this time.
This year, after applying to a great many colleges and universities, I received an especially fine crop of rejection letters. Unfortunately, the number of rejections that I can accept is limited.
Each of my rejections was reviewed carefully and on an individual basis. Many factors were taken into account - the size of the institution, student-faculty ratio, location, reputation, costs and social atmosphere.
I am certain that most colleges I applied to are more than qualified to reject me. I am also sure that some mistakes were made in turning away some of these rejections. I can only hope they were few in number.
I am aware of the keen disappointment my decison may bring. Throughout my deliberations, I have kept in mind the time and effort it may have taken for you to reach your decision to reject me.
Keep in mind that at times it was necessary for me to reject even those letters of rejection that would normally have met my traditionally high standards.
I appreciate your having enough interest in me to reject my application. Let me take the opportunity to wish you well in what I am sure will be a successful academic year.

SEE YOU IN THE FALL!
John Doe

ID:2715347_10102242364979428
Name:Leo Buscaglia Quotes at BrainyQuote.com
Story:N/A
Message:So I am trying to get back into running and today I set out to run/walk a 3ish mile loop.  As I was running over this bridge, I stopped to walk about a third of the way over.  Right as I start walking I hear a voice say "come on, you got this to the end of the bridge...run with me."  This super nice guy gave me just the right encouragement at just the right time to push me through a tough spot.  I ran the rest of the way to my hotel.  Thanks fellow runner for the encouragement!

"Too often we underestimate the power of a touch, a smile, a kind word, a listening ear, an honest compliment, or the smallest act of caring, all of which have the potential to turn a life around."

Leo Buscaglia

1. My Prius.  She gets me where I need to go and does it pretty cheaply.  
2.  My family.  If you know me, you know how awesome they are.  
3. My house.  It may sound silly, but I'm pretty attached to my little abode.  I've learned a lot about myself and life during the 7 years I've lived there by myself.  

Today I challenge Natasha Smyth Marko to list 3 things for which she is thankful for 7 days in a row.
ID:2715347_10102230112802888
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:So I'm accepting Jennifer Hansen Brinkman's challenge to list 3 things for which I'm thankful for 7 days and to challenge some other people.  Sorry in advance to my friends that things like this annoy.  I'm still thankful for you :)

So for today here goes:

1.  TCTW or Teens' Camping Tour of the West.  14 years ago when I stepped on a van full of people I didn't know, I would have never imagined that I just started an adventure that would lead me to my life's passion.  TCTW has connected me to so many people and so many places that have all impacted my life in some way.  I carry a piece of every person I meet and every place I travel with me everywhere I go.  I can't imagine my life without TCTW.

2.  Punky Brew-Brew.  She is a challenge for me at times, but I love her a lot, especially her wet kisses.

3.  Statesville.  I know I want to get out of here right now, but I love this little town.  Statesville will always be home no matter where I end up!

Message:Greetings, cadets! 

First off, I know everyone from our Squadron is not yet linked to our Facebook, so please share with them this information in this post. 

The purpose of this page is to share ideas, give information about social and volunteer events we can attend together as a squadron, how we're doing with honor squadron and warrior squadron, and motivate and encourage each other throughout the semester. I encourage you to not be afraid to share ideas you may have that you think we all will benefit from as a group. If anyone has any idea of what to do for our first initial group outing, go ahead and comment on this post.

Message:It's been 12 year long process from the time I was 7 and first baptized of my life being turned inside out and upside down, it took ups and downs the loss of loved ones the change in where I am and who I am how I think, love, hurt and feel bringing people in and out of my life, being sad and angry all the time for me to realize that I was living wrong and not pleasing him. As I sat and tried to study at 1am today I found myself unable to continue with this path and the way my life was going and he stepped in and moved me to breaking reminding me the times I failed him in trying to prove myself to the world and how many times I was wrong then he took me into his heart and changed mine and at that moment I rededicated my life to him and somehow 10 hours later I was standing at the baptismal pool at Grace Church moved by God into a public statement of change and obedience to him. I have to thank him for all I went through this year and for allowing me to find people like Sade' Wilson, Tommie Chavis, Amos Fung, Esther Aesle Chun, Jazzmine Willis, Michael Ortiz, and Steve Heineman to strengthen me and my walk with him for if it wasn't for them and the situations of this past year I wouldn't be able to say that I am changed and unlike I was before and ready to live my life not just as a Christian but as his child. "I don't have time to maintain these regrets when I think about the way that he loves us, oh how he loves us"

Story:N/A
Message:Greetings, cadets! 

First off, I know everyone from our Squadron is not yet linked to our Facebook, so please share with them this information in this post. 

The purpose of this page is to share ideas, give information about social and volunteer events we can attend together as a squadron, how we're doing with honor squadron and warrior squadron, and motivate and encourage each other throughout the semester. I encourage you to not be afraid to share ideas you may have that you think we all will benefit from as a group. If anyone has any idea of what to do for our first initial group outing, go ahead and comment on this post. 

Just a reminder of who has what job in the squadron for this rotation:

Squadron Commander - C/3C Wilson
Deputy Squadron Commander - C/3C Hamlet
Academic Officer - C/3C Dinh
Physical Fitness Officer - C/3C McQueen
Health and Safety Officer - C/4C Fontalvo
Standardization Officer - C/4C Greth

C/3C McQueen will also be creating a phone tree for tomorrow morning. See you all dark and early!

ID:811929336_887738351255782
Name:null
Story:Reghan Horman uploaded a file in the group DET 590 Cadets.
Message:Some post-PFA notes

1. The Wing Average was a 90. (GMC-86/POC-96) This is an excellent start to the semester, but still leaves a lot of room for improvement. 
2. Your score sheets will be in your box by COB tomorrow. I have all the information I need so they are yours to keep. 
3. Attached is a document which I have found helpful. This will help remind you for the next PFA how much you slept, what the conditions were, etc. It will help you create good habits before the assessment. I leave it at the discretion of Squadron Physical Fitness Officers to require that it be completed. 
4. I am very impressed with your physical capabilities so far this semester. On Thursday we will hopefully be doing a 9/11 Memorial Run and I hope I will be just as impressed with your Warrior Ethos. Get those jodies ready.

Message:Some last minute notes for tomorrow's PFA.

1) Here are the pairings for tomorrow's PFA. They look like Mentor/Mentees BUT with some adjustments so as to make sure pairs are the same gender.
2) Bring the AF Form 30 posted under SharePoint Fall 2014 -> Operations Group-> Physical Fitness Squadron Commander-> Miscellaneous.
3) Music devices WITH headphones are allowed for the run portion tomorrow as long as you keep the music at a reasonable volume.

Make sure your alarms are set, your phone trees are ready, and you're really well stretched. See you all tomorrow morning!

Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:A few IMPORTANT housekeeping notes for PT.

1. The code to open Eddie Smith Field House is 5128#. I trust that you all will use this code responsibly and only for PT.
2. You all now have this code to avoid leaving doors propped open, especially with trashcans. I know that I'm definitely guilty of this, but in the future this will no longer be acceptable. 
3. Be good stewards of the facilities we use for PT. It is a privilege, not a right that we have access to them for PMT events. This includes putting trashcans back to where they were if we move them and picking up empty plastic water bottles (even if they aren't yours, recycle them) but most importantly leaving the facilities the same, if not better than we found them.

See you all at Hooker Fields this afternoon for some awesome soccer.

Message:About a year and a half ago I embarked on my journey to become an Officer in the United States Air Force. Through struggles and triumphs, through growth and falters, through conflict and support, through every single up and down I experienced, today I found out it was all worth it! I received my EA for Field Training today, and I will be among those cadets selected to attending Field Training this summer! I know we have all work incredibly hard and are about to begin the next huge chapter of our lives! I can't wait to be with you guys as POC next year! I love you all so much and support you to the absolute fullest! See you this summer! Field Training 2014 HUA!

Message:Alright! I have been a little bit of a slacker in the past few days, so here is a gigantic post.

It is time for the new flight positions.

CC - Hanha Hobson
CD - Chris Calderado
D&C - Michael Paul
STANDO - Sade' Wilson
ACADO - Connor Hamlet
SAFEO - Estelle McQueen
PFO - Alex Zorich

ORI

For Tuesday's ORI. You will all be in Service Dress. Please make sure you are looking up the regs and spending A LOT of time to make sure it is right. There is a lot to go wrong in the setup, and Cadre will find the mistakes.

I will be acting as the FLT/CC
Cadet Knight will be the deputy
The element leaders will be Cadets Strawser, Hobson, and Horman.
Cadet Calderado will be the guidon bearer.

YOU MUST STUDY THE PROCEDURES. This is not a Lead Lab to learn how to do an ORI. It is a Lead Lab to EXECUTE and ORI. Study with your flight mates, and ask plenty of questions before we start.
Watch this video: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mSuVRRPx0RM

Reveille and Retreat

These are happening on Tuesday. You will not need to learn or do much of anything that is not explicitly commanded, but READ THE OPS ORDERS. Reveille will be at 0715!

Guidon

We need to start working on this in earnest. We need to have a plan for our pole at least before Spring Break.

Lastly

WE ARE CLOSING THE GAP IN WARRIOR AND HONOR. Keep up the great work on that! Let's crush this inspection!

Message:ATTENTION AS200s (AS100s also welcome): 
UNC Chapel Hill is hosting a year-long conversation during 2014-2015 on the legacy of World War I. The World War I Centenary Project seeks to increase awareness of and interest in the war?s impact among faculty, students and the community beyond the University. The conversation kicks off with an academic conference and public roundtable featuring scholars Andrew Lambert and William Philpott of King's College London and Sam Williamson of UNC-Chapel Hill.

? Opening Panel, Aug. 28, 3?5 p.m. Hyde Hall

? Public Roundtable Discussion, Aug. 28, 7?9 p.m., Gerrard Hall

? Academic Conference, Aug. 29, 8:30 a.m.?5 p.m., Hyde Hall

Please be aware of these events, if you are able to attend it is a great opportunity.
ID:1330462999_1453331841598813
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:EXPECTATIONS: Below I am going to post a list of expectations I have for each of you this semester. Keep in mind this is not everything, but a good source to refer throughout the semester. 
EVERYONE MUST LIKE THIS POST when you have READ it COMPLETELY. 

Motivation - show you want to be here and are excited to be here!
Resources - use your wingmen when you need help and have questions. I am here to help, but I am not a crutch.
Respect - a given.
Problems/Feedback - come to me whenever you feel is necessary. I am here for you!
Education - academics are Det. 590s first priority, plan ahead, use time wisely, etc.  
TeamWork! - the success of this Squadron is up to you guys, together!
Attendance - and that includes being attentive and involved when you are.
Customs & Courtesies - respect out Air Forces rules and traditions.
On time - this goes with attendance, but also with deadlines, etc. 
Uniform- respect the uniform, wear it properly.
Take Risks - this is the time for you to grow! Try new things, and LEARN from your mistakes. 

If you have any questions let me know, I can't wait to see where you all take Squadron 3 this semester!

Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:I just had the most spectacular, incredible, and magical night of my entire life! I am so fortunate to be able to do and experience such amazing things! I swam with Manta Rays tonight, in the brilliant Pacific Ocean! They were within inches from my face! It was an honor to be in the water with this gentle giants and hundreds of Hawaiian fish. On the boat ride home I got to see a 300 million dollar yatch that left me in Aw. I watched the stars as we went back to the harbor. I reflected and thought of how thankful I am for this life when then, to top off adventurous evening, a shooting star went across the sky. This world is filled with wonders that can do nothing but leave us speechless. The world we live in is still beautiful and I'm am so grateful to be apart of it.

Story:N/A
Message:On this day 13 years ago, I was living in Upstate New York watching the towers collapse on TV at my elementary school. My dad was deployed almost immediately following one of our nations biggest tragedies. As someone who was affected and remembers vividly how scared my classmates and I were when we were told to hide under our desks in case of another attack, I would like to thank all of our soldiers and armed forced who work so tirelessly to protect our country. You sacrifice so hopefully my children will never have to go through the same heartbreak. My heart goes out to anyone who lost a loved one during the fall of the towers. I can say I am proud to live in this country and lucky beyond measure.

Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Female Cadets: There has been an update to the Regulations pertaining to the hairstyles you are authorized to wear in uniform:

Female Hair Standards Language Revision goes into effect today 12 August 2014
 
1. Effective immediately the language in paragraph 3.1.3.2 has been revised as follows:
n 3.1.3.2. Braids, micro-braids and cornrows are authorized. However, they must be a natural looking color similar to the individual's hair color; conservative (moderate, being within reasonable limits; not excessive or extreme) and not present a faddish appearance.
A braid is three or more portions/strands of interwoven hair. When worn, multiple braids shall be of uniform dimension, small in diameter (approx ? inches), show no more than ? inch of scalp between the braids and must be tightly interwoven to present a neat, professional and well-groomed appearance. Braids must continue to the end of the hair in one direction, in a straight line, and may be worn loose or a secured style within hair standards in paragraph 3.1.3 above. Dreadlocks, (defined as portions of hair that have been intentionally or unintentionally fused together to form a loc or locs), shaved head, flat-tops and military high-and-tight cuts are not authorized hairstyles for female Airmen.

In a nutshell: Natural-color, small, closely-spaced cornrows/braids are now authorized.
ID:1541912236_877357878960496
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Cadets,

It has come down from both the Department of Defense and the Commander of AFROTC that members of AFROTC (and the DoD as a whole) are not to participate in the ALS Ice Challenge while wearing official uniforms or detachment garments. The official announcement from Col Wydra can be found here:

?While a noble cause, cadre and cadets cannot participate it in an official capacity--i.e. representing the AF, AFROTC or your det.  If cadets do want to participate, it would have to be done via non AF and AFROTC organizations like a cadet booster club, Arnold Air Society or Silver Wings.  If cadets do participate in this challenge via these student organizations, please ensure that they are not wearing their uniforms or clothing such as det T-shirts.?

If you want to do this challenge, please feel free, but remember that you are not to use your uniform in ways that may be misconstrued to represent DoD or Air Force official support for a cause.

ID:1641722764_10204041522911997
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:home today don't know if its a good thing watching 9/11 stories but there is always something surprising.  Last year there was the story of the flotillas helping people sail out of NY.  Today a little bit about the Canadians who took care of the diverted international flights.  Will always remember trying to get out of DC on that day and passing by the burning Pentagon.  I took such a long time to get home, it took an hour and a half to go one block with traffic jammed all police officers surrounding the white house no helping the exodus.  We had to assist a disabled coworker get home to Arlington.  Men with briefcases were directing traffic out of DC.  Still don't think DC has an emergency exit plan.  Thankful to all the first responders, its a memory I hope gets less painful with time.  I can't even imagine.

Message:Good evening Squadron 3! I hope everyone is excited for Dining In tomorrow. Just a few notes I want to leave before you all go to bed:

First: When it comes to PT, being the best does NOT mean just achieving excellence by yourself. Motivation does not just mean yelling across from the field house "How you doing Det 590?" It means achieving excellence as a unit, a team. It means motivating and looking out for those beside you, not leaving your wingman behind. What good is reaching the top if there is no one there beside you to share that victory? Continue to work hard as a squadron, but also bring your wingmen up with you.
Second: Know your Warrior Knowledge (Hint Hint) for Reporting-In tomorrow! Look at the post on the Det Page about Reporting and Rules. 
Third: We seem to be losing some motivation as a squadron. Tonight/ tomorrow before LLAB I want you all to comment with a new chant/something that we can say for Tuesdays.
Have a great night, get some rest and get excited for tomorrow!

Message:Have you ever been in a situation where you as a bystander want to intervene, but don?t know how? Do you know what an unhealthy relationship looks like? These are three great programs here on campus that emphasize your role as an active bystander and promote an inclusive, safe community. Take the next steps to prevent violence on campus. Each program has its own training dates and requires registration.

One Act: A program that to stop interpersonal violence here on UNC campus and empower bystanders. What One Act will you do? 

Safe Zone: Committed to diversity and inclusiveness, this program aims to make our community a safer and supportive place for people of all sexual orientations, gender identities, and gender expressions. 

Haven: A three hour training session and program to provide students with tools and skills to be an ally to someone who has experienced sexual or interpersonal violence or stalking.

For more information on One Act and Haven, please visit safe@unc.edu and for more information on Safe Zone visit http://lgbtq.unc.edu/programs-services/safe-zone

Message:I've done a lot of growing up lately... Realizing that things aren't always what they seem. People aren't always who they say they are. Things aren't always going to go the way you hope. Time is not going to wait. Good things aren't going to just be handed to you. Life is hard. Decisions are difficult to make. The right thing to do is not always the easiest thing to so. School is stressful. Crying is okay. You are worth it. Treat your body right, work out. Eat. Drink in the beautiful moments. Make happy memories, not ones you will regret. You're beautiful. People are blind. You will make it. God is real. True friends are to be kept close. Stop trying to be "good enough" because you already are. Negativity is not a strong anchor. Family is for a lifetime. It's okay to say no. Your mother is to be cherished. You will make a lot of mistakes. But you know what, that's okay. Don't let your mistakes define who you are. Win some, lose some. That's how it goes, right? What is really important & what really matters will never be lost. You just have to learn the difference, & I'm still learning.

Message:There is no such thing as privacy. Nothing you do will be ineffective. Everything you do will effect all of us...

Even if you do something in secret, there is always at least one person present?you.  In case you hadn?t noticed, your actions change you. And if your actions change you, and you influence the people with whom you interact, then by the transitive property your actions (even if done in secret) influence the people with whom you interact. So whether or not you think you?re ?alone,? you?re actually changing the entire world one action at a time. 

Brothers and sisters, this is GREAT news! This means that whenever you demonstrate love towards God and man?whether in public or in secret?the whole world rejoices and the ripple of your act can be seen, the echo of your act can be heard, in ten thousands of hearts for ten thousands of  years!

But take care. Remember, there is no such thing as privacy. Nothing you do will be ineffective. Everything you do will effect all of us. Please don?t betray your neighbour by doing something sinful or foolish in secret. For just as the world is blessed through your love and diligence, the world is cursed through your hatred and negligence. Church: neither take part in nor tolerate sin, but go unto Christ and follow ye Him (and read up on your 1 Corinthians while your at it; it?s a rockin? awesome book).

In short, take every opportunity to think a kind thought, to speak a kind word, to demonstrate a loving deed?whatever you think, say, or do in public or in private, do it for love of God and for love of those around you, and you will bless the entire world.

I know not what path other men may take; but as for me and my house, we will serve the Lord.

Message:Until today, I used to think God was selfish for so often reminding us to love, serve, and worship Him. Who but the most egotistical and selfish would require such praises from men?

But then I discovered what a joy it is to love someone, freely and deeply, without any self-centred ulterior motives or expectations in return. 

And I realized that God loves us selflessly, without a thought for Himself. Creating and providing, He sings to us from Aurora to Dawn, He dances for us a dance of majesty, He soars in the delight it brings Him to love us freely and without measure. 
It delights Him to be our Servant, to show us love in every way, even to the death on the cross, and even to the resurrection.

And then I realized that the invitation to worship and love Him, to give Him everything, was an invitation to join in the joy and delight of loving someone the way He loves us--wholly and completely, without reservation and without expectation. He doesn't require our worship for His sake--Christ is Christ with or without our praise. Rather, he invites us to worship Him for our sakes, to know what it is like to return the love He has already given to us, to delight in love and to bring our hearts to life. 

"And so my child I give this gift to you and all the nations so you can give it back to me one day." --Theocracy--

Message:Cadets,

For your WK quiz tomorrow, not only will you need to know the ten major commands and the Cadet Honor Code, but there will be a section specifically for either 100s or 200s. You will only need to answer questions that are aimed toward your class, and only those will be scored. However, the 100s are welcome to answer the 200s questions, because eventually you will need to know it. For the 200s, let the 100s questions serve as a review. 

100s: when to salute and the place of honor, WK handbook (sharepoint)
200s: the academic build protocol, FTM

Message:Greetings, cadets! 

First off, I know everyone from our Squadron is not yet linked to our Facebook, so please share with them this information in this post. 

The purpose of this page is to share ideas, give information about social and volunteer events we can attend together as a squadron, how we're doing with honor squadron and warrior squadron, and motivate and encourage each other throughout the semester. I encourage you to not be afraid to share ideas you may have that you think we all will benefit from as a group. If anyone has any idea of what to do for our first initial group outing, go ahead and comment on this post. 

Just a reminder of who has what job in the squadron for this rotation:

Squadron Commander - C/3C Wilson
Deputy Squadron Commander - C/3C Hamlet
Academic Officer - C/3C Dinh
Physical Fitness Officer - C/3C McQueen
Health and Safety Officer - C/4C Fontalvo
Standardization Officer - C/4C Greth

C/3C McQueen will also be creating a phone tree for tomorrow morning. See you all dark and early!

We are doing football bag checking again this fall! I received the official schedule and we will be working the games on September 6th and October 18th. ID:100000532471065_820397071321368
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:21!

A while back, I wrote myself a list to make sure I'd stay true to myself as I went through college. Even though there are new experiences and choices, always remember where you came from:




1. Don?t give up on a dream. If you have to change something to go after something better, do it. Use your best judgment and don?t regret anything. If you make the wrong choice, don?t worry about how hard you fall ? you?re still in the fight.

2. Don?t let anything distract you. Drugs, alcohol abuse, bad people, bad experiences. Nothing gets in the way of a dream. No struggle is too big for God. And no dream is worth extinguishing from a breeze of a problem. Everything?s a breeze when you?re on God?s team.

3. If you?re alone in a journey, find someone for support. If you don?t, God is a wingman, it will pan out. Always has so far.

4. Remember how much you?ve accomplished and what morals and values you live for. The long term high road wins 100% of the time over a short term quick plan that doesn?t work. Or an impulse.

5. Remember if you do take a risk on something, don?t freak out if some perfect record messes up or anything is permanent. You?ll only stay stuck on that when you could press past something you could learn from and be better as a result of that experience.

6. No matter how many people don?t seem to be on your side, there?s a family somewhere to support you no matter what. Football, Air Force, immediate, best friends, whoever. They?re always on reserve if you need them.

7. You need to stay inspired. Don?t get satisfied or complacent. Keep yourself motivated.

8. Stay humble. If you succeed, make sure you?re an example, not a trophy.

9. Rob Jones says to write the word humble twice. Humble.

10. And finally, every major event or struggle in life is God reminding you that He?s in control, and He has a plan. If you trust it, you?ll be taken care of. There?s a lesson in everything, and every challenge is an opportunity for a testimony.

Thank you to everyone who was a part of this special day - Rob Jones, Michael DeMaria, Ginny Lawson, Christian Willis

ID:100001247926336_862752550421029
Name:Reviresco Run
Story:N/A
Message:This Tuesday (July 29), there is an opportunity to help veterans as they reintegrate into civilian society. A group of West Point cadets is running from Newark, Delaware to Houston, Texas to raise money and awareness for veterans. Along the way, they are trying to get cadets or midshipmen from any branch of ROTC to join in for a few miles when they pass by their school. The Reviresco Run will be passing right through UNC on July 29 at noon! I've been told that the portion you could join in for is about 3 miles. It's not a race, just a way to help veterans and have some fun. I found out about this on somewhat short notice, so I cannot be in Chapel Hill for it, as I live in St. Louis. If you can participate in this run, please contact me ASAP. My number is (314)550-6639. Also, this isn't exclusive to military, since one of the goals of the event is to build military/civilian relations and understanding. Bring your friends! The money they raise will be given to Team Red, White, and Blue and Got Your 6. Below I have attached a quick video explaining what Reviresco is. Let me know if you have any questions! https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VucN6URljgY

ID:100001329792269_623963050991349
Name:Open Ranks Inspection
Story:N/A
Message:Alright! I have been a little bit of a slacker in the past few days, so here is a gigantic post.

It is time for the new flight positions.

CC - Hanha Hobson
CD - Chris Calderado
D&C - Michael Paul
STANDO - Sade' Wilson
ACADO - Connor Hamlet
SAFEO - Estelle McQueen
PFO - Alex Zorich

ORI

For Tuesday's ORI. You will all be in Service Dress. Please make sure you are looking up the regs and spending A LOT of time to make sure it is right. There is a lot to go wrong in the setup, and Cadre will find the mistakes.

I will be acting as the FLT/CC
Cadet Knight will be the deputy
The element leaders will be Cadets Strawser, Hobson, and Horman.
Cadet Calderado will be the guidon bearer.

YOU MUST STUDY THE PROCEDURES. This is not a Lead Lab to learn how to do an ORI. It is a Lead Lab to EXECUTE and ORI. Study with your flight mates, and ask plenty of questions before we start.
Watch this video: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mSuVRRPx0RM

Reveille and Retreat

These are happening on Tuesday. You will not need to learn or do much of anything that is not explicitly commanded, but READ THE OPS ORDERS. Reveille will be at 0715!

Guidon

We need to start working on this in earnest. We need to have a plan for our pole at least before Spring Break.

Lastly

WE ARE CLOSING THE GAP IN WARRIOR AND HONOR. Keep up the great work on that! Let's crush this inspection!

Message:Something I wrote exactly two years from tomorrow:
UNC football is the beautiful North Carolina fall weather.
 It is the sound of Kenan Stadium when Charles Brown destroys a screen to Travis Benjamin.
 It is the comfortable feeling of home, and the tension of fighting for the all-important victory.
 It is the band marching to the Stadium.
 It is tailgating with your buddies.
 It is Tar Heel Town, and the Old Well Walk.
 It is the ceremony of pregame and halftime.
 It is no one knowing the words to Tar Heels on Hand.
 It is respect for our opponents, though we are certain to dominate.
 It is the fans.
 It is bleeding Carolina blue.
 It is that united feeling of 63,000 people working for the same goal.
 It is the legends of Charlie Justice and Lawrence Taylor.
 It is the alma mater, and Carolina Victory.
 It is the Tar Pit, loud and boisterous, providing boundless energy to their classmates, and dancing to Stick it in and 234.
 It is an attitude of never taking a play off, no matter the score.
 It is the Victory Bell.
 It is Ramses, and his blue horns.
 It is the Bell Tower ringing before, during, and after the game.
 It is giving everything you got whether you?re a fan, coach, or player.
 It is emotional.
 It is smart, fast, and physical.
 UNC football is here. As students, we don?t get these Saturdays forever. Make them count.

Message:Cadets: It's Detachment 590 T-shirt ordering time!  The Det T-shirt, which is gray with the Det logo, interlocking NC, and Air Force Symbol, is not only great on it's own merit, but also approved for PT use, meaning if everyone has one we could all wear it to PT every now and then (So they're Highly Recommended).  For any cadets who don't already have one, they'll only cost $5.  For everyone else, they'll be $19.  I need to have shirt sizes before I can order the shirts, so all shirt sizes must be put on the googledoc below before COB Monday.  Money is due to me (or my mailbox) by COB Friday, 5 September.  Side note: They aren't UnderArmour, they're going to be Holloway Zoom Tees.  Ask me questions if you have them.

https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/13xwTGZGT7CrRUWqasOc4ouxC_PUAMiKJle4BriEUPB4/edit?usp=sharing

Name:Stadium Cleanups Signup - Google Sheets
Story:N/A
Message:Cadets, it is time to sign up for football stadium cleanups once again!  The good news is, there's only 42 slots to sign up, so we all only have to do one cleanup each this season!  All cleanups will be on Sunday morning (7am to ~3pm) after the game, and you are absolutely required to be there the entire time the team is cleaning up.  Bring dirty clothes, old shoes, portable music to keep yourself entertained, and sign up on the googledoc please!  We need 12 to sign up for next Sunday (8 days away) by Monday, but it would be so much better if all the slots were taken by then.  For those unaware, as fun as this sounds, it's a very important way Det 590 pays for a lot of things, so sign up and support your fellow cadets!    Of course, ask questions if you have them.  https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1gLINcPPAtoPBWkNyNcoQEPLmDXpiYPRuJjrAh9D9AtI/edit?usp=sharing

ID:100004246980031_302602929891271
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:?Here's what I learned over the years. Know the mission, what is expected of you and your people. Get to know those people, their attitudes and expectations. Visit all the shops and sections. Ask questions. Don't be shy. Learn what each does, how the parts fit into the whole. Find out what supplies and equipment are lacking, what the workers need. To whom does each shop chief report? Does that officer really know the people under him, is he aware of their needs, their training? Does that NCO supervise or just make out reports without checking facts? Remember, those reports eventually come to you. Don't try to bullshit the troops, but make sure they know the buck stops with you, that you'll shoulder the blame when things go wrong. Correct without revenge or anger. Recognize accomplishment. Reward accordingly. Foster spirit through self-pride, not slogans, and never at the expense of another unit. It won't take long, but only your genuine interest and concern, plus follow-up on your promises, will earn you respect. Out of that you gain loyalty and obedience. Your outfit will be a standout. But for God's sake, don't ever try to be popular! That weakens your position, makes you vulnerable. Don't have favorites. That breeds resentment. Respect the talents of your people. Have the courage to delegate responsibility and give the authority to go with it. Again, make clear to your troops you are the one who'll take the heat.? 
? Robin Olds

Time to finish this semester off strong, put this behind me, and prepare for the amazing Senior year I have coming!
